# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 30-by-30
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:30-by-30/2010-biodiversity-indicators-partnership] The **Biodiversity Indicators Partnership** (BIP) brings together a host of international organizations working on indicator development, to provide the best available information on biodiversity trends to the global community.
[src:30-by-30/2010-biodiversity-indicators-partnership] The Partnership was initially established to help monitor progress towards the Convention on Biological Diversity (CBD) 2010 Biodiversity target.
[src:30-by-30/2010-biodiversity-indicators-partnership] However, since its establishment in 2006 the BIP has developed a strong identity not only within the CBD but with other Multilateral Environmental Agreements (MEAs), national and regional governments and other sectors.
[src:30-by-30/2010-biodiversity-indicators-partnership] As a result, the Partnership will continue through international collaboration and cooperation to provide biodiversity indicator information and trends into the future.
[src:30-by-30/2010-biodiversity-indicators-partnership] Central to the renewed Partnership will be its revitalized relationship with the Convention on Biological Diversity.
[src:30-by-30/2010-biodiversity-indicators-partnership] In 2010, at the 10th Conference of the Parties to the CBD held in Nagoya, Japan the BIP was referenced eight times in the official adopted decisions.
[src:30-by-30/2010-biodiversity-indicators-partnership] These references demonstrated a clear will for the Partnership to continue supporting the CBD with implementation of the Strategic Plan for Biodiversity 2011–2020.
[src:30-by-30/2010-biodiversity-indicators-partnership] The Strategic Plan consists of 20 new biodiversity targets for 2020, termed the ‘Aichi Biodiversity Targets’.
[src:30-by-30/2010-biodiversity-indicators-partnership] Biodiversity encompasses the entire variety of life on Earth.
[src:30-by-30/2010-biodiversity-indicators-partnership] It is vital for human survival and is a key measure of the health of our planet.
[src:30-by-30/2010-biodiversity-indicators-partnership] Human activities are irreversibly impacting biodiversity.
[src:30-by-30/2010-biodiversity-indicators-partnership] In all regions of the world species extinction rates have increased, ecosystems have been degraded, and genetic diversity has declined.
[src:30-by-30/2010-biodiversity-indicators-partnership] An essential part of reaching the 2010 biodiversity target was being able to measure and communicate progress.
[src:30-by-30/2010-biodiversity-indicators-partnership] For this purpose the CBD adopted a framework in 2004, which included the use of a range of biodiversity indicators to measure progress towards the 2010 target.
[src:30-by-30/2010-biodiversity-indicators-partnership] In 2006 this framework was further elaborated and the '*2010 Biodiversity Indicators Partnership* was established, as a global initiative to further develop and promote indicators for the consistent monitoring and assessment of biodiversity.
[src:30-by-30/2010-biodiversity-indicators-partnership] The 2010 BIP was established with major support from the Global Environment Facility (GEF).
[src:30-by-30/2010-biodiversity-indicators-partnership] The main objective of the Partnership is a reduction in the rate of biodiversity loss at the global level, through improved decisions for the conservation of global biodiversity.
[src:30-by-30/2010-biodiversity-indicators-partnership] To establish links between biodiversity initiatives at the national and regional levels to enable capacity building and improve the delivery of the biodiversity indicators.
[src:30-by-30/2010-biodiversity-indicators-partnership] Through CBD governance and advisory bodies, the global biodiversity community identified a suite of 17 headline indicators from the seven focal areas for assessing progress towards, and communicating the 2010 target at a global level.
[src:30-by-30/2010-biodiversity-indicators-partnership] Since 2007, partners have worked to ensure the most accurate information is available to decision makers.
[src:30-by-30/2010-biodiversity-indicators-partnership] The BIP indicators have substantially contributed to the 3rd edition of the *Global Biodiversity Outlook*, featuring in the *Status and Trends in Biodiversity* chapter of this flagship CBD publication.
[src:30-by-30/2010-biodiversity-indicators-partnership] The Partnership also works to integrate indicator results into coherent, compelling storylines giving a more understandable picture of the status of biodiversity.
[src:30-by-30/2010-biodiversity-indicators-partnership] The Partnership brings together a host of international organisations working to support the regular delivery of biodiversity indicators at the global, national and regional levels.
[src:30-by-30/2010-biodiversity-indicators-partnership] The BIP works to communicate links between the partnership’s work and all potential users, including highlighting the utility of the components of the CBD indicator suite for other multilateral environmental agreements.
[src:30-by-30/2010-biodiversity-indicators-partnership] Engagement with the private sector is also an objective for the partnership.
[src:30-by-30/2010-biodiversity-indicators-partnership] The BIP has provided financial support and currently provides ongoing technical support to the Global Reporting Initiative (GRI), to advance the integration of related indicators into corporate performance measures.
[src:30-by-30/2010-biodiversity-indicators-partnership] In addition to improving global-scale indicators, the BIP has been actively involved in supporting national and regional initiatives; facilitating indicator development and implementation that responds to country-specific national biodiversity priorities.
[src:30-by-30/2010-biodiversity-indicators-partnership] A programme of capacity building workshops has been run across the globe, bringing together the various institutional representatives involved in national indicator development to share experiences and best-practice.
[src:30-by-30/2010-biodiversity-indicators-partnership] Some 45 countries have been engaged to date.
[src:30-by-30/2010-biodiversity-indicators-partnership] A series of guidance documents on national indicator development have been published, together with a web portal (www.bipnational.net).
[src:30-by-30/2010-biodiversity-indicators-partnership] This multi-language website is the most comprehensive online resource of guidance, support and shared experiences of effective indicator development for countries and regions looking to develop biodiversity indicators.
[src:30-by-30/2010-biodiversity-target] The **2010 Biodiversity Target** was an overall conservation target aiming to halt the decline of biodiversity by the end of 2010.
[src:30-by-30/2010-biodiversity-target] The world largely failed to meet the target.
[src:30-by-30/2010-biodiversity-target] It was first adopted by EU Heads of State at the EU Summit in Gothenburg, Sweden, in June 2001.
[src:30-by-30/2010-biodiversity-target] They decided that "biodiversity decline should be halted with the aim of reaching this objective by 2010".
[src:30-by-30/2010-biodiversity-target] One year later, the Convention on Biological Diversity's sixth Conference of the Parties adopted the Strategic Plan for the Convention in Decision VI/26.
[src:30-by-30/2010-biodiversity-target] The World Summit on Sustainable Development held in Johannesburg in 2002 confirmed the 2010 Biodiversity Target and called for "the achievement by 2010 of a significant reduction in the current rate of loss of biological diversity".
[src:30-by-30/2010-biodiversity-target] By the year 2006, the following nations have contributed extensively to establishment of individual Biodiversity Action Plans: Tanzania, New Zealand, Great Britain and the United States of America, called Species Recovery Plans in the USA.
[src:30-by-30/2010-biodiversity-target] The 2004 Irish Presidency held a major stakeholder conference on the 2010 Biodiversity Target which resulted in a detailed roadmap to 2010 called the "Message from Malahide".
[src:30-by-30/2010-biodiversity-target] At the same time, a number of organisations joined to launch the initiative Countdown2010 to support progress towards the 2010 Biodiversity Target.
[src:30-by-30/2010-biodiversity-target] On May 22, 2006 the European Commission launched its Biodiversity Communication as an implementation tool to reach the 2010 Biodiversity Target.
[src:30-by-30/2010-biodiversity-target] Subsequent Convention on Biological Diversity (CBD) decisions went on to specify indicators (see: Biodiversity Indicators Partnership) for immediate testing and for possible use, and to further develop work programmes for implementation of the target.
[src:30-by-30/2010-biodiversity-target] This decision poses the question of how to measure the rate of biodiversity loss, in order to assess whether the target has been achieved by the nations who are party to the Convention.
[src:30-by-30/2012-hyderabad-biodiversity-conference] The **2012 Hyderabad Conference** of the Parties to the UN Convention on Biological Diversity (CBD), also known as COP11, was held in Hyderabad, India.
[src:30-by-30/2012-hyderabad-biodiversity-conference] Environment ministers and forests ministers of about 194 countries attended the conference; international organizations like World Bank and the Asian Development Bank also participated.
[src:30-by-30/2012-hyderabad-biodiversity-conference] Nearly 10,000 delegates discussed issues relating to biodiversity and biosafety.
[src:30-by-30/2012-hyderabad-biodiversity-conference] The COP11 logo consists of three major motifs, the Royal Bengal Tiger on the upper part, a woman with a bird and a leaf at the center and a dolphin on the lower part of the circle.
[src:30-by-30/2012-hyderabad-biodiversity-conference] The Royal Bengal tiger represents all the terrestrial animals.
[src:30-by-30/2012-hyderabad-biodiversity-conference] The Royal Bengal Tiger is an endangered species, and one of the main aims of CBD, is to reduce biodiversity loss.
[src:30-by-30/2012-hyderabad-biodiversity-conference] Thus, it conveys the distinctive character of the origination and its activities.
[src:30-by-30/2012-hyderabad-biodiversity-conference] The family Delphinidae is the largest in the Cetacean order, they are found all over the world, and thus it represents the world aquatic life.
[src:30-by-30/2012-hyderabad-biodiversity-conference] The Woman represents The Mother Earth, who provides us with food, shelter and every basic necessity of human and other living creatures.
[src:30-by-30/2012-hyderabad-biodiversity-conference] The woman in the logo is winnowing grain in a typical Indian style representing Indian culture.
[src:30-by-30/2012-hyderabad-biodiversity-conference] The leaf and the bird stand for the flora and fauna.
[src:30-by-30/2012-hyderabad-biodiversity-conference] They are vital for our nature to survive.
[src:30-by-30/2012-hyderabad-biodiversity-conference] Thus they represent the balance of nature.
[src:30-by-30/2012-hyderabad-biodiversity-conference] There are 22 official and 398 living languages in India.
[src:30-by-30/2012-hyderabad-biodiversity-conference] Amidst this lingual diversity, Sanskrit holds the thread of oneness as many of these languages are derived from Sanskrit.
[src:30-by-30/2012-hyderabad-biodiversity-conference] The English translation is placed circling the lower rim.
[src:30-by-30/2012-hyderabad-biodiversity-conference] Also it represents the circle of life, the dogma of our nature.
[src:30-by-30/2012-hyderabad-biodiversity-conference] In Indian philosophy, a circle is a bindu, a metaphysical term, which is proposed to be the point of origin of all the creation.
[src:30-by-30/2012-hyderabad-biodiversity-conference] A circle has no beginning or end, thus symbolizing the universe in itself.
[src:30-by-30/2022-united-nations-biodiversity-conference] The conference was originally scheduled to be held in October 2020, but was delayed due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:30-by-30/2022-united-nations-biodiversity-conference] It was rescheduled to be held in April 2022 in Kunming, China, but was postponed again, for a fourth time due to China's zero-COVID policy, to the third quarter of 2022 according to the UN secretariat office on March 29.
[src:30-by-30/2022-united-nations-biodiversity-conference] In May 2022, China requested Canada to assume the host responsibility.
[src:30-by-30/2022-united-nations-biodiversity-conference] The Canadian Minister of Environment and Climate Change Steven Guilbeault met with representatives from the High Ambition Coalition in early June 2022 and these representatives asked Canada to host COP15.
[src:30-by-30/2022-united-nations-biodiversity-conference] The Prime Minister of Canada Justin Trudeau approved the proposal.
[src:30-by-30/2022-united-nations-biodiversity-conference] In June 2022, the UN secretariat for the Convention on Biological Diversity and China's environment ministry said in separate statements that the meeting would be held in December 2022 in Montreal, Canada, where the secretariat is based, though China would remain the president of the summit.
[src:30-by-30/2022-united-nations-biodiversity-conference] While the host countries of previous COPs had one to two years to organize the conference, Canada had just five months to prepare for the arrival of 18,000 delegates from 196 CBD member states, non-governmental organizations, industry groups and academia.
[src:30-by-30/2022-united-nations-biodiversity-conference] This is the second time Montreal served as the host city for a UN Conference of Parties meeting, the first time being the COP11 climate change conference in 2005.
[src:30-by-30/2022-united-nations-biodiversity-conference] Montreal also played host to the negotiations for the Montreal Protocol.
[src:30-by-30/2022-united-nations-biodiversity-conference] Several cities signed the "Montreal Pledge" in advance of the conference to commit to protect biodiversity in their cities through 15 actions.
[src:30-by-30/2022-united-nations-biodiversity-conference] During the talks, divisions remained on numerous issues as the conference went into its final days, such as disputes over the funding for conservation efforts.
[src:30-by-30/2022-united-nations-biodiversity-conference] There was also discussion that protections for marine biodiversity could be dropped completely.
[src:30-by-30/2022-united-nations-biodiversity-conference] An op-ed published in *The Guardian* in mid-December criticized the proceedings as being very slow and lacking urgency.
[src:30-by-30/2022-united-nations-biodiversity-conference] On December 19, almost every country on earth signed onto the agreement which includes protecting 30% of land and oceans by 2030 (30 by 30) and 22 other targets intended to reduce biodiversity loss.
[src:30-by-30/2022-united-nations-biodiversity-conference] When the agreement was signed only 17% of land territory and 10% of ocean territory were protected.
[src:30-by-30/2022-united-nations-biodiversity-conference] The agreement includes protecting the rights of indigenous peoples and changing the current subsidy policy to a one better for biodiversity protection.
[src:30-by-30/2022-united-nations-biodiversity-conference] However, it makes a step backward in protecting species from extinction in comparison to the Aichi Targets.
[src:30-by-30/2022-united-nations-biodiversity-conference] Some countries said the agreement does not go far enough to protect biodiversity, and that the process was rushed.
[src:30-by-30/2022-united-nations-biodiversity-conference] Only the United States and the Holy See did not join it.
[src:30-by-30/2022-united-nations-biodiversity-conference] The absence of the United States signature weakened the agreement.
[src:30-by-30/2022-united-nations-biodiversity-conference] However, the country helped to reach the agreement, strongly advanced some of the targets mentioned in it, especially 30 by 30, nationally and internationally and is a major donor to biodiversity protection issues.
[src:30-by-30/2022-united-nations-biodiversity-conference] In addition to protecting 30% of land and oceans by 2030, the agreement includes also recovering 30% of earth degraded ecosystems and increasing funding for biodiversity issues.
[src:30-by-30/2022-united-nations-biodiversity-conference] Other targets for the year 2030 include cutting overconsumption and waste, reducing food waste by 50%, and completely stop harming ecosystems that are strongly important for biodiversity.
[src:30-by-30/2022-united-nations-biodiversity-conference] There are also 4 targets for the year 2050 which includes increasing the area of natural ecosystems, restoring their integrity and normal functioning, reducing tenfold the human caused extinction rate, and protecting traditional knowledge.
[src:30-by-30/2022-united-nations-biodiversity-conference] The advocacy of the UNCBD Women's Cacus and its members led to a Rio Convention for the first time in its 30-year history to adopt a stand-alone target, **Target 23**, on gender equality in the Kunming-Montreal Global Biodiversity Framework.
[src:30-by-30/2024-united-nations-biodiversity-conference] The **2024 United Nations Biodiversity Conference of the Parties (COP16)** to the UN Convention on Biological Diversity (CBD) was a conference that was held from 21 October to 1 November 2024, in Cali, Colombia.
[src:30-by-30/2024-united-nations-biodiversity-conference] The monitoring framework agreed at the previous conference should allow the progress of the countries towards national goals and targets under the Kunming-Montreal Global Biodiversity Framework to be evaluated.
[src:30-by-30/2024-united-nations-biodiversity-conference] On 11 December 2023, the Minister of Environment and Sustainable Development of Colombia, Susana Muhamad, announced that the country had officially offered to host the COP16, which was scheduled to be held from 21 October to 1 November 2024.
[src:30-by-30/2024-united-nations-biodiversity-conference] On 20 February 2024, the President of Colombia, Gustavo Petro, announced that Cali had been chosen to host the event, after a month-long competition with Bogotá.
[src:30-by-30/2024-united-nations-biodiversity-conference] The COP16's official logo was presented by the Minister of Environment and Sustainable Development of Colombia, Susana Muhamad, and the interim executive secretary of the UNCBD, David Cooper, on 28 February 2024, during the Sixth UN Environment Assembly in Nairobi, Kenya.
[src:30-by-30/2024-united-nations-biodiversity-conference] The UNCBD COP16 mainly aimed to review progress of the countries towards the goals set by the Kunming-Montreal Global Biodiversity Framework (GBF), which had been approved in December 2022, having set 23 general targets to "halt and reverse biodiversity loss" by 2030.
[src:30-by-30/2024-united-nations-biodiversity-conference] According to the inquiry, only five of the 17 megadiverse countries (Australia, China, Indonesia, Malaysia and Mexico), as well as four G7 nations (Canada, France, Italy and Japan), submitted their respective NBSAPs by the deadline.
[src:30-by-30/2024-united-nations-biodiversity-conference] Representatives for Colombia announced that the country would present its own plan during the meeting, while spokespersons for the United Kingdom, Brazil and India stated that the nations would not publish their respective NBSAPs earlier than 2025.
[src:30-by-30/2024-united-nations-biodiversity-conference] The COP16 was also considered as an occasion to review other goals set at the previous conference in Montreal, including an agreement to provide developing countries with at least US$20 billion to finance the implementation of conservation targets by 2025, and at least $30 billion a year by 2030.
[src:30-by-30/2024-united-nations-biodiversity-conference] Another target included in the Global Biodiversity Framework urged countries to identify funding to nature-damaging sources and cut them by $500 billion a year by the end of the decade.
[src:30-by-30/2024-united-nations-biodiversity-conference] Upon the start of the meeting, only seven developed countries had contributed to the Global Biodiversity Framework Fund (GBFF), donating a total of $244 million.
[src:30-by-30/2024-united-nations-biodiversity-conference] Finally, a draft of a global action plan on biodiversity and health was reportedly set to be negotiated at the conference.
[src:30-by-30/2024-united-nations-biodiversity-conference] According to a yearly Global Witness report about victims of violence and repression against environmental activism, released in September 2024, 196 environmentalists and activists around the world had been murdered throughout 2023.
[src:30-by-30/2024-united-nations-biodiversity-conference] Colombia topped the list for the second year in a row, with 79 killings (19 more than the year prior), followed by Brazil, with 25 killings, and by Mexico and Honduras, with 18 killings per each.
[src:30-by-30/2024-united-nations-biodiversity-conference] The report also raised concerns about growing repression and censorship of protests led by environmentalist associations in several countries, including the United Kingdom, France, Italy, Germany and the Netherlands.
[src:30-by-30/2024-united-nations-biodiversity-conference] In the wake of further threats by the EMC and failed terrorist attacks in Cali and Jamundí, it was reported that thousands of members of the Army and the National Police were expected to be deployed in Cali to ensure the safety of delegates and citizens.
[src:30-by-30/2024-united-nations-biodiversity-conference] On 30 July, the leader of the EMC, Néstor Gregorio (also known by the nom de guerre Iván Mordisco), announced that the units of the group would not affect any events related to the COP16 "as a gesture of [their] will for peace".
[src:30-by-30/2024-united-nations-biodiversity-conference] The executive secretary of the Convention on Biological Diversity, Astrid Schomaker, said that her staff had "worked very closely" with national, regional and local authorities to arrange effective security arrangements for the COP16.
[src:30-by-30/2024-united-nations-biodiversity-conference] On 21 October 2024, the inaugural day of the meeting, Muhamad presented Colombia's own NBSAP, called *Plan de Acción por la Biodiversidad 2030* ("Plan of Action for Biodiversity 2030").
[src:30-by-30/2024-united-nations-biodiversity-conference] The document — which was estimated to require a total investment of 76.5 billion pesos, roughly corresponding to over US$17.8 billion — set six national goals and 191 targets needed to fulfill the 2022 Global Biodiversity Framework by the end of the decade.
[src:30-by-30/2024-united-nations-biodiversity-conference] During the first week of the convention, representatives of Indigenous and Afro-descendant communities, as well as civil society associations, were involved in dedicated international forums.
[src:30-by-30/2024-united-nations-biodiversity-conference] Some analysts and participants also noted how the funding for developing countries required by the GBF was "a drop in the sea" in comparison to incentives paid by governments to providers of nature-damaging sources.
[src:30-by-30/2024-united-nations-biodiversity-conference] The conference closed on 2 November 2024, with no agreement on a roadmap to ramp up funding for species protection.
[src:30-by-30/2024-united-nations-biodiversity-conference] It was suspended as negotiations ran almost twelve hours longer than planned and delegates started leaving to catch flights.
[src:30-by-30/2024-united-nations-biodiversity-conference] The exodus left the summit without a quorum for decision-making.
[src:30-by-30/2024-united-nations-biodiversity-conference] Delegates did agree earlier to form a subsidiary body for recognizing Indigenous peoples' role, including traditional environmental knowledge, in future decisions on conservation.
[src:30-by-30/2024-united-nations-biodiversity-conference] The body is led by two co-chairs, one of which is nominated by UN parties of the regional group and the other nominated by indigenous peoples and local communities.
[src:30-by-30/2024-united-nations-biodiversity-conference] The role of people of African descent in the protection of nature was also recognized.
[src:30-by-30/2024-united-nations-biodiversity-conference] An agreement was also reached earlier on charging large biotechnology companies who derive genetic information from living organisms with a 0.1% fee.
[src:30-by-30/2024-united-nations-biodiversity-conference] The fee is to recognize that many life-saving medicines and genetic resources are derived from organisms living in biodiversity hotspots, such as the tropical rainforest.
[src:30-by-30/2024-united-nations-biodiversity-conference] The collected fee was set to go into a newly established fund to protect nature, with 50% allocated towards Indigenous communities.
[src:30-by-30/2024-united-nations-biodiversity-conference] An extended session of the COP16 was held in Rome, Italy, at the headquarters of the Food and Agriculture Organization, from 25 to 27 February 2025.
[src:30-by-30/2024-united-nations-biodiversity-conference] The president of the conference, Susana Muhamad, took part in the meetings, despite having resigned from her role as Minister of Environment and Sustainable Development of Colombia on 9 February, in protests to cabinet appointments by President Gustavo Petro.
[src:30-by-30/2024-united-nations-biodiversity-conference] The plan included commitment to raise US$20 billion in annual conservation financing by 2025, with the assets being set to rise to US$30 billion annually by 2030; according to the latest data collected at the time by the OECD, countries had managed to raise just US$15 billion towards the same goals.
[src:30-by-30/2024-united-nations-biodiversity-conference] Ministers of finance and environment from all of the countries were also expected to hold an "international dialogue" to ensure the targets would be reached.
[src:30-by-30/2024-united-nations-biodiversity-conference] The consequent progress would be reviewed at the COP17 in 2026, hosted by Armenia.
[src:30-by-30/2024-united-nations-biodiversity-conference] On the other hand, negotiations on a new fund for nature finance were suspended and postponed to 2028, due to disagreements between the delegations involved on the status of the Global Environment Facility (GEF).
[src:30-by-30/2024-united-nations-biodiversity-conference] Developing countries, including Brazil and the African Group, considered the GEF as too burdensome to access and over-representing wealthier nations, and demanded the creation of a newly established fund. hosted by COP committees.
[src:30-by-30/30-by-30] US$5 billion in funding for a project called the "Protecting Our Planet Challenge" was announced for the initiative in September 2021.
[src:30-by-30/30-by-30] In December 2022, 30 by 30 was agreed at the COP15 meeting of the Convention on Biological Diversity, and became a target of the Kunming-Montreal Global Biodiversity Framework.
[src:30-by-30/30-by-30] This includes the G7 and European Union.
[src:30-by-30/30-by-30] The initiative has attracted controversy over indigenous rights issues.
[src:30-by-30/30-by-30] As of May 2026, 17.3% of terrestrial land and inland waters and 9.8% of marine areas are protected.
[src:30-by-30/30-by-30] Including OECM's (Other Effective Area-based Conservation Measures) the percent of protected areas are 18.4% of terrestrial and inland waters and 10.0% of marine areas.
[src:30-by-30/30-by-30] The European Commission's Biodiversity strategy for 2030 was proposed on May 20, 2020, as the European Union's contribution to a post-2020 global biodiversity framework.
[src:30-by-30/30-by-30] The plan includes turning 30% of EU territory to protected area by 2030 and 10% to strictly protected area.
[src:30-by-30/30-by-30] However as of 2023 EU is not on track to meet the targets.
[src:30-by-30/30-by-30] The biodiversity strategy is a core part of the European Green Deal, and also intended to support green recovery from the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:30-by-30/30-by-30] In July 2023 after many debates the European parliament adopted a version of the Nature restoration law, aiming to restore nature on 20% of the territory of the European Union by 2030.
[src:30-by-30/30-by-30] In 2024, the European Union passed a nature restoration law aiming to restore 20% of degraded ecosystems by 2030 and 100% by 2050.
[src:30-by-30/30-by-30] On January 27, 2021, President Joe Biden issued an executive order on "Tackling the Climate Crisis at Home and Abroad".
[src:30-by-30/30-by-30] Participating federal agencies included the U.S.
[src:30-by-30/30-by-30] Department of Commerce, and Council on Environmental Quality.
[src:30-by-30/30-by-30] The order also established a California Biodiversity Collaborative composed of representatives of government agencies, Native tribes, experts, and other stakeholders.
[src:30-by-30/30-by-30] The official report, *Pathways to 30x30 California*, was issued by the California Natural Resources Agency on 22 April 2022.
[src:30-by-30/30-by-30] Implementation of the 30 by 30 target has progressed unevenly, and researchers caution that simply increasing the extent of protected areas is not sufficient to halt biodiversity loss.
[src:30-by-30/30-by-30] Some conservationists argue that the 30% figure lacks a clear scientific justification and risks being treated as a symbolic or political benchmark rather than a threshold grounded in ecological evidence.
[src:30-by-30/30-by-30] At the same time, other researchers and advocacy groups contend that 30% may in fact be too low to secure long‑term ecological integrity, and point to proposals such as the "Half‑Earth" concept, which calls for roughly 50% of terrestrial and marine realms to be conserved in some form.
[src:30-by-30/30-by-30] A further concern relates to the quality and effectiveness of protection once areas are designated.
[src:30-by-30/30-by-30] Researchers and NGOs have highlighted the persistence of so‑called "paper parks": protected areas that exist in law but lack adequate funding, staffing or enforcement, allowing activities such as poaching, illegal logging, or unregulated development to continue.
[src:30-by-30/30-by-30] Modelling work by Kuempel et al. suggests that, for exploited species, improving enforcement and management within existing protected areas can in many cases deliver greater conservation benefits than simply expanding the network’s total area without a corresponding increase in resources.
[src:30-by-30/30-by-30] Taken together, this literature underlines that meeting percentage‑based targets without adequate governance capacity risks diluting scarce conservation resources.
[src:30-by-30/30-by-30] Other research has examined conditions under which expanding protected areas can still be beneficial even when management budgets do not increase.
[src:30-by-30/30-by-30] Their results suggest that, in landscapes where human pressures are spatially clumped near reserve boundaries, strategically increasing the size of protected areas can create more secure habitat refuges even without proportional increases in staffing or enforcement.
[src:30-by-30/30-by-30] In practice, the 30 by 30 commitment has also prompted debate over how "protected" or "conserved" areas are defined for monitoring and reporting purposes.
[src:30-by-30/30-by-30] Implementation of the 30 by 30 target has also raised concerns about “green grabbing” and green colonialism in the way new protected and conserved areas may be established.
[src:30-by-30/30-by-30] Similar critiques have been echoed by human rights organisations and researchers who argue that percentage-based conservation targets can replicate earlier "fortress conservation" models if they are implemented through top-down land designations that disregard customary tenure and existing uses.
[src:30-by-30/30-by-30] More broadly, some Indigenous organisations have criticised the way 30 by 30 has been promoted and negotiated, arguing that it risks appropriating Indigenous lands under the guise of biodiversity conservation.
[src:30-by-30/30-by-30] The COP15 included 196 parties in negotiations, with competing views regarding the adoption of the 30 by 30 target being wide-spread and well documented.
[src:30-by-30/30-by-30] The resulting agreement of the conference, the Convention on Biological Diversity, was signed by every party, with the exception of two: the United States and the Vatican.
[src:30-by-30/30-by-30] Towards the end of the talks, a negotiator from Democratic Republic of the Congo raised objections to the agreement, citing a lack of funding separate from the current Global Environment Facility (GEF).
[src:30-by-30/30-by-30] After a delay, COP15 president and Chinese environment minister Huang Runqiu overruled the objection due to a legal technicality, resulting in the passage of the agreement.
[src:30-by-30/30-by-30] Delegates from the DRC, Cameroon, and Uganda were reportedly displeased with the outcome.
[src:30-by-30/30-by-30] After the agreement was passed, the DRC's government announced that it would not recognize it as valid.
[src:30-by-30/30-for-30] The idea for the series began in 2007 from ESPN.com columnist and Grantland.com founder Bill Simmons and ESPN's Connor Schell.
[src:30-by-30/30-for-30] The title, *30 for 30*, derived from the series's genesis as 30 films in celebration of ESPN's 30th anniversary in 2009, with an exploration of the biggest stories from ESPN's first 30 years on-air, through a series of 30 one-hour films by 30 filmmakers.
[src:30-by-30/30-for-30] Volume I premiered in October 2009 and ran to December 2010, chronicling 30 stories from the "ESPN era", beginning with the network's founding in 1979.
[src:30-by-30/30-for-30] In April 2018, it was announced that the entire archive of *30 for 30* films and shorts would be available on ESPN+, ESPN's direct-to-consumer online platform, once the service launched on April 12, 2018.
[src:30-by-30/30-for-30] The first film, Peter Berg's *Kings Ransom*, a chronicle of Wayne Gretzky's trade from the Edmonton Oilers to the Los Angeles Kings, premiered on October 6, 2009, to poor ratings.
[src:30-by-30/30-for-30] *Kings Ransom* drew a 0.5 national rating and a total viewership of 645,000.
[src:30-by-30/30-for-30] As awareness and critical acclaim grew, the viewing audience also grew.
[src:30-by-30/30-for-30] By the seventh episode, *The U*, the audience had grown to a 1.8 rating and well over 2 million viewers.
[src:30-by-30/30-for-30] Cadillac and Levi's are the presenting sponsors of the series.
[src:30-by-30/30-for-30] The Cadillac name appears on the 30 for 30 logo.
[src:30-by-30/30-for-30] The Levi's "go forth" slogan appears on the bottom corner of the screen during the directors interstitial comments, which appear for 45 seconds at the beginning of each film and 30 seconds at the end.
[src:30-by-30/30-for-30] Commercials for both companies were shown during every intermission during the original air dates, with Levi's guaranteed a 60-second commercial slot at the beginning of the third act.
[src:30-by-30/30-for-30] Cadillac replaced Honda as a primary sponsor.
[src:30-by-30/30-for-30] During its time as a contributor, Honda aired parts of its "Dream the Impossible" documentary series in the first commercial break.
[src:30-by-30/30-for-30] During broadcasts in the UK on BT Sport, these sponsorship logos are blurred out due to compliance regulations.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] The **Associated Press** (**AP**) is an American not-for-profit news agency headquartered in New York City.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] Founded in 1846, it operates as a cooperative, unincorporated association, and produces news reports that are distributed to its members, major U.S. daily newspapers and radio and television broadcasters.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] Since the Pulitzer Prize was established in 1917, the AP has earned 60 of them, including 36 for photography.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] The AP distributes its widely used *AP Stylebook*, its AP polls tracking NCAA sports, and its election polls and results during U.S. elections.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] It sponsors the National Football League's annual awards.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] By 2016, news collected by the AP was published and republished by more than 1,300 newspapers and broadcasters.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] The AP operates 235 news bureaus in 94 countries, and publishes in English, Spanish, and Arabic.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] It also operates the AP Radio Network, which provides twice hourly newscasts and daily sportscasts for broadcast and satellite radio and television stations.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] Many newspapers and broadcasters outside the United States are AP subscribers, paying a fee to use AP material without being contributing members of the cooperative.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] As part of their cooperative agreement with the AP, most member news organizations grant automatic permission for the AP to distribute their local news reports.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] As of 2025, the AP attracts more than 128 million monthly website visits, making it one of the top 10 news websites in the U.S.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] The Associated Press was formed in May 1846 by five daily newspapers in New York City to share the cost of transmitting news of the Mexican–American War.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] The venture was organized by Moses Yale Beach (1800–68), second publisher of *The Sun*, joined by the *New York Herald*, the *New York Courier and Enquirer*, *The Journal of Commerce*, and the *New York Evening Express*.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] Some historians believe that the *New-York Tribune* joined at this time; documents show it was a member in 1849.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] *The New York Times* became a member in September 1851.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] Initially known as the New York Associated Press (NYAP), the organization faced competition from the Western Associated Press (1862), which criticized its monopolistic news gathering and price setting practices.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] An investigation completed in 1892 by Victor Lawson, editor and publisher of the *Chicago Daily News*, revealed that several principals of the NYAP entered into a secret agreement with United Press, a rival organization, to share NYAP news and the profits of reselling it.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] The findings led to the dissolving of the NYAP.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] That December, the Western Associated Press was incorporated in Illinois as the Associated Press.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] A 1900 Illinois Supreme Court decision (*Inter Ocean Publishing Co. v.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] Associated Press*) holding that the AP was a public utility and operating in restraint of trade resulted in the AP's move from Chicago to New York City, where corporation laws were more favorable to cooperatives.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] In 1935, the AP launched the Wirephoto network, which allowed transmission of news photographs over leased private telephone lines on the day they were taken.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] This gave the AP a major advantage over other news media outlets.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] While the first network was only between New York, Chicago, and San Francisco, eventually the AP had its network across the whole United States.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] In 1945, the Supreme Court of the United States held in *Associated Press v.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] United States* that the AP had been violating the Sherman Antitrust Act by prohibiting member newspapers from selling or providing news to nonmember organizations as well as making it very difficult for nonmember newspapers to join the AP.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] The AP entered the broadcast field in 1941 when it began distributing news to radio stations; it created its own radio network in 1974.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] In 1994, it established APTV, a global video newsgathering agency.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] APTV merged with Worldwide Television News in 1998 to form APTN, which provides video to international broadcasters and websites.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] In 2004, the AP moved its headquarters from its long-time home at 50 Rockefeller Plaza to 450 West 33rd Street in Manhattan.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] In 2019, AP had more than 240 bureaus globally.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] Its mission has not changed since its founding, but digital technology has made the distribution of the AP news report an interactive endeavor between the AP and its hundreds of U.S. newspaper members, as well as broadcasters, international subscribers, and online customers.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] The AP began diversifying its news gathering capabilities.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] By 2007, the AP was generating only about 30% of its revenue from United States newspapers, and by 2024, this had declined to 10%.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] 37% came from the global broadcast customers, 15% from online ventures and 18% came from international newspapers and from photography.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] In March 2024, Gannett, the largest U.S. newspaper publisher as measured by total daily circulation, announced that effective March 25, 2024, it would no longer use content from the AP.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] A spokesperson for AP said that they were "shocked and disappointed" by this development.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] Newspaper chain McClatchy announced that it would also stop using some AP services.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] Gannett and McClatchy will both continue to use AP's election results data.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] The AP's multi-topic structure has resulted in web portals such as Yahoo! and MSN posting its articles, often relying on the AP as their first source for news coverage of breaking news items.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] This and the constant updating evolving stories require has had a major impact on the AP's public image and role, giving new credence to the AP's ongoing mission of having staff for covering every area of news fully and promptly.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] In 2007, Google announced that it was paying to receive AP content, to be displayed in Google News, interrupted from late 2009 to mid-2010 due to a licensing dispute.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] A 2017 study by NewsWhip revealed that AP content was more engaged with on Facebook than content from any individual English-language publisher.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] The AP is governed by an elected board of directors.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] Since 2022, the board's chairperson is Gracia C.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] Martore, former president and CEO of Tegna, Inc.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] AP reports from countries where press freedom is restricted, sometimes under adverse circumstances, and operates out of more than 100 regional offices.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] In 2025, restrictions preventing AP reporting in the U.S. were imposed by the second Trump administration.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] In February 2025, two AP reporters were barred from covering several events at the White House, because of the AP refusal to refer to the Gulf of Mexico as the "Gulf of America", as directed by the White House.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] The restrictions against AP were extended to other reporting opportunities such as in Air Force One.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] On February 21, 2025, the AP sued the Trump administration in *Associated Press v.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] Budowich* for blocking their attendance.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] On February 24, 2025, a federal judge declined to issue an immediate order compelling the White House to reinstate access to presidential events to AP, although he encouraged the White House to do so.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] On April 8, 2025, Judge Trevor McFadden ruled that the White House must lift the access restrictions they placed on the AP while the *AP v.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] On June 6, 2025, the United States Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit imposed a stay upon the lower court's order, allowing the White House to resume barring access to some media events.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] The AP is one of two organizations that collect and verify election results in every city and county across the United States, including races for the U.S. president, the Senate and House of Representatives, and governors as well as other statewide offices.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] Known for accuracy, the organization has collected and published presidential election data since 1848.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] Major news outlets rely on the polling data and results provided by the Associated Press before declaring a winner in major political races, particularly the presidential election.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] In declaring the winners, the AP has historically relied on a robust network of local reporters with first-hand knowledge of assigned territories who also have long-standing relationships with county clerks as well as other local officials.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] Moreover, the AP monitors and gathers data from county websites and electronic feeds provided by states.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] The research team further verifies the results by considering demographics, number of absentee ballots, and other political issues that may have an effect on the final results.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] In 2018, the AP introduced a new system called AP VoteCast, which was developed together with NORC at the University of Chicago in order to further improve the reliability of its data and overcome biases of its legacy exit poll.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] The AP conducts polls for numerous college sports in the United States.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] The AP college football rankings were created in 1936, and began including the top 25 teams in 1989.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] Since 1969, the final poll of each season has been released after all bowl games have been played.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] The AP released its all-time Top 25 in 2016.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] As of 2017, 22 different programs had finished in the number one spot of the poll since its inception.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] In the pre-bowl game determination era, the AP poll was often used as the distinction for a national champion in football.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] The AP college basketball poll has been used as a guide for which teams deserve national attention.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] The AP first began its poll of college basketball teams in 1949, and has since conducted over 1,100 polls.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] The college basketball poll started with 20 teams and was reduced to 10 during the 1960–61 college basketball season.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] It returned to 20 teams in 1968–69 and expanded to 25 beginning in 1989–90.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] The final poll for each season is released prior to the conclusion of the NCAA tournament, so all data includes regular season games only.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] In 2017, The AP released a list of the Top 100 teams of all time.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] The poll counted poll appearances (one point) and No.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] 1 rankings (two points) to rank each team.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] The AP began its Major League Baseball Manager of the Year Award in 1959, for a manager in each league.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] From 1984 to 2000, the award was given to one manager in all of MLB.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] The winners were chosen by a national panel of AP baseball writers and radio men.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] Every year, the AP releases the names of the winners of its AP College Basketball Player of the Year and AP College Basketball Coach of the Year awards.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] It also honors a group of All-American players.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] In 1994, London-based Associated Press Television (APTV) was founded to provide agency news material to television broadcasters.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] In 1998, the AP purchased Worldwide Television News (WTN) from the ABC News division of The Walt Disney Company, Nine Network Australia and ITN London.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] The AP publishes 70,000 videos and 6,000 hours of live video per year, as of 2016.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] The agency also provides seven simultaneous live video channels, AP Direct for broadcasters, and six live channels on AP Live Choice for broadcasters and digital publishers.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] The AP was the first news agency to launch a live video news service in 2003.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] The first publicly available edition of the book was published in 1953.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] The first modern edition was published in August 1977 by Lorenz Press.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] Afterwards, various paperback editions were published by different publishers, including, among others, Turtleback Books, Penguin's Laurel Press, Pearson's Addison-Wesley, and Hachette's Perseus Books and Basic Books.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] Recent editions are released in several formats, including paperback and flat-lying spiral-bound editions, as well as a digital e-book edition and an online subscription version.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] Additionally, the *AP Stylebook* also provides English grammar recommendations through social media, including Twitter, Facebook, Pinterest, and Instagram.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] From 1977 to 2005, more than two million copies of the *AP Stylebook* were sold worldwide, with that number climbing to 2.5 million by 2011.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] Writers in broadcasting, news, magazine publishing, marketing departments, and public relations firms traditionally adopt and apply AP grammar and punctuation styles.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] The AP collaborated with Nazi Germany and gave it access to its photographic archives for its antisemitic Nazi propaganda.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] AP also cooperated with the Nazi regime through censorship.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] In 2017, the German historian Norman Domeier of the University of Vienna brought to wider attention the deal between the AP and the Nazi government related to the interchange of press photos during the period in which the United States was at war with Nazi Germany.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] This relationship involved the Bureau Laux, run by the Waffen-SS photographer Helmut Laux.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] The mechanism for this interchange involved a courier flying to Lisbon and back each day transporting photos from and for Nazi Germany's wartime enemy, the United States, via diplomatic pouch.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] The transactions were initially conducted at the AP bureau under Luiz Lupi in Lisbon, and from 1944, when the exchange via Lisbon took too long, also at the AP bureau in Stockholm under Eddie Shanke.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] Here, as a cover, the Swedish agency, Pressens Bild, was involved as an intermediary.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] An estimated 40,000 photos were exchanged between the enemies in this way.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] The AP was kicked out of Nazi Germany when the United States entered World War II in December 1941.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] Israeli journalist Matti Friedman accused the AP of killing a story he wrote about the "war of words", "between Israel and its critics in human rights organizations", in the aftermath of the 2008–2009 Gaza war.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] On September 29, 2000, the first day of the Second Intifada, the AP published a photograph of a badly-bloodied young man behind whom a police officer could be seen with a baton raised in a menacing fashion; a gas station with Hebrew lettering could also be seen in the background.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] The AP labelled it with the caption "An Israeli policeman and a Palestinian on the Temple Mount", and the picture and caption were subsequently published in several major American newspapers, including the *New York Times*.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] In reality, the injured man in the photograph was a Jewish yeshiva student from Chicago named Tuvia Grossman, and the police officer, a Druze named Gidon Tzefadi, was protecting Grossman from a Palestinian mob who had clubbed, stoned, and stabbed Grossman.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] There are also no gas stations with Hebrew lettering on the Temple Mount.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] The episode is often cited by those who accuse the media of having an anti-Israel bias, and was the impetus for the founding of the pro-Israel group HonestReporting.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] After a letter from Grossman's father noted the error, the AP, the *New York Times*, and other papers published corrections; despite these corrections, the photograph continues to be used by critics of Israel as a symbol of Israeli aggression and violence.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] During the 2021 Israel–Palestine crisis, the Israeli army destroyed the al-Jalaa Highrise, a building housing the AP's Gaza offices and Al Jazeera offices.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] Israel stated that the building housed Hamas military intelligence and had given advanced warning of the strike, and no civilians were harmed.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] AP CEO Gary Pruitt released a statement on May 16, stating that he "had no indication Hamas was in the building" and called on the Israeli government to provide the evidence.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] On May 17, US secretary of state Antony Blinken said he had not seen any evidence that Hamas operated from the building housing the AP and Al Jazeera, but it is the job of others to handle intelligence matters.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] Israel reportedly shared intelligence with American officials and U.S. president Joe Biden showing Hamas offices inside the building.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] Reporters Without Borders asked the International Criminal Court to investigate the bombing as a possible war crime.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] On June 8, the Israeli ambassador to the US, Gilad Erdan, met with AP CEO Gary Pruitt and vice president for foreign news, Ian Phillips, to discuss the operation.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] In coordination with the IDF, Erdan said the site was used by Hamas intelligence officials to develop and carry out electronic warfare operations, and that IDF did not suspect the AP was aware of the alleged covert Hamas presence.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] After the meeting the AP stated "We have yet to receive evidence to support these claims".
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] In May 2024, Israeli officials seized equipment broadcasting a live stream of Northern Gaza from the town of Sderot as part of a ban on Al Jazeera Media in Israel which had received footage from the broadcast.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] The move was condemned by multiple journalism organizations, Israeli opposition politicians, and US government officials.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] In 1994, Tina Susman was on her fourth trip to Somalia, reporting for the AP.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] She was reporting on U.S. peacekeeping troops leaving the country.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] Somali rebels outnumbered her bodyguards in Mogadishu, dragged her from her car in broad daylight, and held her for 20 days.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] She told *The Quill* that she believes being a woman was an advantage in her experience there.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] The AP had requested news organizations including *The New York Times*, the *Chicago Tribune,* and *The Washington Post* to suppress the story to discourage the emboldening of the kidnappers.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] In September 2002, Washington, D.C. bureau reporter Christopher Newton, an AP reporter since 1994, was fired after he was accused of fabricating sources since 2000, including at least 40 people and organizations.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] Prior to his firing, Newton had been focused on writing about federal law enforcement while based at the Justice Department.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] Some of the nonexistent agencies quoted in his stories included "Education Alliance", the "Institute for Crime and Punishment in Chicago", "Voice for the Disabled", and "People for Civil Rights".
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] In 2007, an FBI agent working in Seattle impersonated an AP journalist and infected the computer of a 15-year-old suspect with malicious surveillance software.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] The incident sparked a strongly worded statement from the AP demanding that the bureau never impersonate a member of the news media again.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] In September 2016, the incident resulted in a report by the Justice Department, which the AP said "effectively condone[d] the FBI's impersonation".
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] In December 2017, following a US court appearance, a judge ruled in favor of the AP in a lawsuit against the FBI for fraudulently impersonating a member of the news media in conjunction with the 2007 case.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] In June 2008, the AP sent numerous DMCA take-down demands and threatened legal action against several blogs.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] The AP contended that the internet blogs were violating the AP's copyright by linking to AP material and using headlines and short summaries in those links.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] Many bloggers and experts noted that the use of the AP news fell squarely under commonly accepted internet practices and within fair-use standards.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] Others noted and demonstrated that the AP routinely takes similar excerpts from other sources, often without attribution or licenses.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] The AP responded that it was defining standards regarding citations of AP news.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] In March 2009, the AP counter-sued artist Shepard Fairey over his famous image of Barack Obama, saying the uncredited, uncompensated use of an AP photo violated copyright laws and signaled a threat to journalism.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] Fairey had sued the AP the previous month over his artwork, titled "Obama Hope" and "Obama Progress", arguing that he did not violate copyright law because he dramatically changed the image.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] The artwork, based on an April 2006 picture taken for the AP by Mannie Garcia, was a popular image during the 2008 presidential election and now hangs in the National Portrait Gallery in Washington, D.C.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] According to the AP's lawsuit filed in federal court in Manhattan, Fairey knowingly "misappropriated The AP's rights in that image".
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] The suit asked the court to award the AP profits made off the image and damages.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] Fairey said he looked forward to "upholding the free expression rights at stake here" and disproving the AP's accusations.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] In January 2011, the suit was settled with neither side declaring their position to be wrong but agreeing to share reproduction rights and profits from Fairey's work.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] In January 2008, the AP sued competitor All Headline News (AHN) claiming that AHN allegedly infringed on its copyrights and a contentious "quasi-property" right to facts.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] The AP complaint asserted that AHN reporters had copied facts from AP news reports without permission and without paying a syndication fee.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] After AHN moved to dismiss all but the copyright claims set forth by the AP, a majority of the lawsuit was dismissed.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] The case has been dismissed and both parties settled.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] On April 23, 2013, hackers posted a tweet to AP's Twitter account about fictional attacks on the White House, falsely claiming that President Obama had been injured.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] The hoax caused a flash crash on the American stock markets, with the Dow Jones Industrial Average briefly falling by 143 points.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] On May 13, 2013, the AP announced that telephone records for 20 of their reporters during a two-month period in 2012 had been subpoenaed by the U.S.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] Justice Department and described these acts as a "massive and unprecedented intrusion" into news-gathering operations.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] The DOJ did not direct subpoenas to the AP, instead going to their phone providers, including Verizon Wireless.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] Attorney General Eric Holder testified under oath in front of the House Judiciary Committee that he recused himself from the leak investigations to avoid any appearance of a conflict of interest.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] Holder said his Deputy Attorney General, James M.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] Cole, was in charge of the AP investigation and would have ordered the subpoenas.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] On January 10, 2022, AP announced it would start selling non-fungible tokens (NFTs) of their photographs in partnership with a company named Xooa, with the proceeds being used to fund their operations.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] One of the NFTs they promoted on Twitter on 24 February was an aerial shot depicting an overcrowded migrant boat in the Mediterranean Sea by Brazilian photojournalist Felipe Dana.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] The sale received negative backlash from users and other journalists, with AP being accused of profiting off of human suffering and the picture choice being "dystopian" and "in extremely poor taste".
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] The tweet was subsequently deleted and the NFT, which was to be sold the next day, was pulled from market.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] Global director of media relations Lauren Easton apologized, saying "This was a poor choice of imagery for an NFT.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] It has not and will not be put up for auction ...
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] AP's NFT marketplace is a very early pilot program, and we are immediately reviewing our efforts".
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] The AP has earned 59 Pulitzer Prizes, including 36 for photography, since the award was established in 1917.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] In May 2020, Dar Yasin, Mukhtar Khan, and Channi Anand of the AP were honored with the 2020 Pulitzer Prize for Feature Photography.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] The choice caused controversy, because it was taken by some as questioning "India's legitimacy over Kashmir" as it had used the word "independence" in regard to revocation of Article 370.
[src:30-by-30/ap-news] The AP won an Oscar in 2024 for the documentary film *20 Days in Mariupol*, a first-person account of the early days of Russia's invasion of Ukraine in 2022.
